00:35:38.780 --> 00:35:43.270
So how can you be competitive
if you're not doing this

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:47.880
experimentation and not getting
to excellence from the

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:50.620
get-go, because it saves
you a lot of time if

00:35:50.620 --> 00:35:52.630
you just keep improving?

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:55.230
HIROSHI MIKITANI: I completely
agree with you.

00:35:55.230 --> 00:36:00.380
And I would like to know the
secrets of how to overcome

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:01.300
those issues.

00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:09.460
And yes, Japanese people are
extremely critical against the

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:12.600
initial launch of the
service as well.

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:16.650
In the past, we made several
failures to be very honest.

00:36:16.650 --> 00:36:20.720
And it's kind of difficult
to come back.

00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:22.780
But you need to be patient.

00:36:22.780 --> 00:36:30.390
And I think in these days you
need to be open about all

00:36:30.390 --> 00:36:34.970
these, how do you call it,
shortcomings and the mistakes

00:36:34.970 --> 00:36:39.060
and very candid about it.

00:36:39.060 --> 00:36:43.670
So some US company says this
is better service.

00:36:43.670 --> 00:36:48.850
Why are you criticizing us so
much, kind of mentality.

00:36:48.850 --> 00:36:53.310
But I think in Japan, I
don't know why, but it

00:36:53.310 --> 00:36:54.170
doesn't work that way.

00:36:54.170 --> 00:37:02.110
I think you need to be, how do
you call it, closer to the

00:37:02.110 --> 00:37:07.330
final perfect service
before the launch.

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:09.920
AUDIENCE: I guess as a quick
follow-up, in collaboration

00:37:09.920 --> 00:37:12.600
with international acquisitions
and things like

00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:15.990
that, so at Google for example,
we share a document

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:18.860
with other team members
and then we keep

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:20.600
improving on that document.

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:23.670
I especially pay very special
attention when I'm sharing

00:37:23.670 --> 00:37:26.460
with a Japanese co-worker
because they expect a

00:37:26.460 --> 00:37:30.610
super-high level of quality,
not something that is

00:37:30.610 --> 00:37:31.560
growing over time.

00:37:31.560 --> 00:37:37.110
So I guess how do you enforce or
enable better collaboration

00:37:37.110 --> 00:37:39.630
between the Japanese employees
and the international

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:41.180
counterparts?

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:47.540
HIROSHI MIKITANI: So the first
step was this language, the

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:51.370
project to communicate
in English.

00:37:51.370 --> 00:37:57.790
And two, I think not only just
sharing online, but really

00:37:57.790 --> 00:38:02.510
having a face-to-face
interaction is a very, very

00:38:02.510 --> 00:38:03.650
important I feel.

00:38:03.650 --> 00:38:07.670
That we need to build
the sense of team.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:11.280
And at the same time, I think
what is important is to

00:38:11.280 --> 00:38:17.050
educate, knowing the Japanese,
the engineers and the product

00:38:17.050 --> 00:38:21.240
managers in Japan has a
different expectation for

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:23.025
level of the service.

00:38:26.210 --> 00:38:28.820
DANIEL ALEGRE: Do you reward
smart failure?

00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:29.770
HIROSHI MIKITANI: Of course.

00:38:29.770 --> 00:38:30.660
Of course, yes.

00:38:30.660 --> 00:38:33.120
DANIEL ALEGRE: How do you
do that in Japan?

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:41.860
HIROSHI MIKITANI: Well first of
all, we have never punished

00:38:41.860 --> 00:38:48.240
the failure, unless it's the
intentional misconduct.

00:38:48.240 --> 00:38:52.340
Of course, we had some
system down.

00:38:52.340 --> 00:38:54.290
We had a big fraud [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:54.290 --> 00:38:55.340
in the past.

00:38:55.340 --> 00:39:02.270
But we never really punished
the mistake.

00:39:02.270 --> 00:39:06.580
But I think encouraging--

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:10.450
we have the sort of
award every month.

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:13.810
We give the [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:13.810 --> 00:39:16.690
award to many, many people.

00:39:16.690 --> 00:39:21.400
And we encourage
the sort of new

00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:24.420
innovation and new creation.

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:27.740
AUDIENCE: Hi, Mickey.

00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:28.690
My name is Tony Kam.

00:39:28.690 --> 00:39:31.180
I'm responsible for working
with the US team.

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:32.550
So I'm with [INAUDIBLE]
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:34.580
They have been great to us.

00:39:34.580 --> 00:39:37.210
I have a request and
a question for you.

00:39:37.210 --> 00:39:37.920
HIROSHI MIKITANI: Request, OK.

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:40.000
AUDIENCE: The rumor is that
you're talking to the Dodgers

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:41.720
for potential ownership.

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:43.090
We love the Giants here.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:46.210
Would you consider perhaps
a different team?

00:39:46.210 --> 00:39:49.940
We don't want them to have
better ownership there.

00:39:49.940 --> 00:39:52.770
My question is where do you
find your inspiration?

00:39:52.770 --> 00:39:55.770
You have some very different
idea, not very

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:57.010
conventional ideas.

00:39:57.010 --> 00:39:59.390
How do you find your inspiration
along the way and

00:39:59.390 --> 00:40:02.750
how do you test them
along the way?

00:40:02.750 --> 00:40:06.340
HIROSHI MIKITANI: Well, it's a
difficult question because I

00:40:06.340 --> 00:40:08.680
never been the other person.

00:40:08.680 --> 00:40:11.920
And this is a very
natural for me.

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:18.440
But I think it's all about
applying something you've seen

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:22.670
in a different environment
to other fields and

00:40:22.670 --> 00:40:27.550
cross-applying the same
theory to it.

00:40:27.550 --> 00:40:31.230
And if you think about like
shopping, you need to step

00:40:31.230 --> 00:40:35.540
back and think why people buy
product, instead of thinking

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.820
about how we can
compete against

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:40.200
Amazon in terms of price.

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:42.060
I think stepping back, standing

00:40:42.060 --> 00:40:45.020
back, and having this--

00:40:45.020 --> 00:40:45.290
holistic?

00:40:45.290 --> 00:40:46.260
DANIEL ALEGRE: Holistic.

00:40:46.260 --> 00:40:51.130
HIROSHI MIKITANI: --view
of the scene is

00:40:51.130 --> 00:40:52.500
very important I think.

00:40:55.470 --> 00:40:57.880
I don't know why, but
I have that kind of

00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:00.820
the habit and tendency.

00:41:00.820 --> 00:41:01.490
AUDIENCE: My name is Joel.

00:41:01.490 --> 00:41:03.880
I work on Google's new
product and service.

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:09.900
So product listing ads is one
product that we're supporting.

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:11.630
So I guess my question
has two part.

00:41:11.630 --> 00:41:15.210
One part is about the general
challenges for Rakuten itself.

00:41:15.210 --> 00:41:18.010
Like what do you think is the
main challenge for Rakuten,

00:41:18.010 --> 00:41:20.960
especially for example we talk
about competitions, like

00:41:20.960 --> 00:41:23.180
Google has its product
listing ads.

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:25.320
I'm looking at the revenues
growing very fast.

00:41:25.320 --> 00:41:28.430
And what is other like
sorts of competition

00:41:28.430 --> 00:41:29.810
you can think of?

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:32.630
And my second question is about
the opportunity for

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:33.230
e-commerce.

00:41:33.230 --> 00:41:35.870
Because we know e-commerce has
been there for a long time,

00:41:35.870 --> 00:41:38.340
like I don't know, over
15 years probably.

00:41:38.340 --> 00:41:41.510
So what is new opportunities you
can think of e-commerce in

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.190
general, for all
the companies?

00:41:43.190 --> 00:41:45.930
Like I really like to talk about
like taking for example,

00:41:45.930 --> 00:41:48.780
like in personal, more customer
service like the

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:50.110
purchasing experience.

00:41:50.110 --> 00:41:53.230
And also you keep [INAUDIBLE]
more experience to personalize

00:41:53.230 --> 00:41:54.850
the way that they
sell products.

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:57.580
But are there other
opportunities you can think of

00:41:57.580 --> 00:41:59.300
for e-commerce in general?

00:41:59.300 --> 00:42:01.030
Thank you.

00:42:01.030 --> 00:42:04.230
HIROSHI MIKITANI: First of all,
I think there are so many

00:42:04.230 --> 00:42:06.920
rooms for improvement
for Rakuten.

00:42:06.920 --> 00:42:10.660
And basically now we
are building our

00:42:10.660 --> 00:42:13.350
own logistic network.

00:42:13.350 --> 00:42:17.620
And we are building our last
one-mile delivery.

00:42:17.620 --> 00:42:20.930
I think we will be able
to do this in Japan.

00:42:20.930 --> 00:42:22.810
The question is whether we
can do this in other

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:24.180
countries or not?

00:42:24.180 --> 00:42:26.750
Japan is relatively
dense country.

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:29.680
It is a little bit larger the
size of California and we have

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:31.920
130 million population
and delivery network

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:32.640
is reasonably good.

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:34.210
So we can do it.

00:42:34.210 --> 00:42:38.770
But if you go to other
countries, can we do as good

00:42:38.770 --> 00:42:42.390
logistic service, including in
the future last one-mile

00:42:42.390 --> 00:42:45.370
delivery or not?

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:49.110
I think it's totally different
scale of story and we need to

00:42:49.110 --> 00:42:50.820
consider that.

00:42:50.820 --> 00:42:54.070
For the future opportunity,
I everybody talk

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:55.920
about social shopping.

00:42:55.920 --> 00:43:03.170
And whether we can figure it out
to really how we can scale

00:43:03.170 --> 00:43:07.430
the social shopping or
not is really the

00:43:07.430 --> 00:43:10.000
opportunity and challenge.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:13.870
That is the reason why we
invested in Pinterest.

00:43:13.870 --> 00:43:15.280
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:17.560
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much
for your time and your

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:18.630
openness to talk to us here.

00:43:18.630 --> 00:43:19.130
I'm Manny.

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:22.140
I work in our global team.

00:43:22.140 --> 00:43:24.090
I'm from Europe and
Play.com is one

00:43:24.090 --> 00:43:25.220
of my favorite websites.

00:43:25.220 --> 00:43:27.300
And I think what's amazing about
it is that it has free

00:43:27.300 --> 00:43:29.100
deliveries wherever
you are in Europe.

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:31.700
And really, it has been a reason
to not buy anywhere

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:34.630
else just because of this, even
though potentially it can

00:43:34.630 --> 00:43:36.660
be more expensive.

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:38.690
How come the global [INAUDIBLE]
still haven't sold

00:43:38.690 --> 00:43:43.040
this delivery issue yet?s I
mean, it's maybe a follow-up

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:44.355
on the previous question.

00:43:44.355 --> 00:43:49.170
But it's incredible that some
companies and some sites can

00:43:49.170 --> 00:43:51.110
offer completely free delivery
to wherever you are in the

00:43:51.110 --> 00:43:55.220
world, whereas you can pay
almost 30% to 40% of whatever

00:43:55.220 --> 00:43:57.535
your price is for the same
delivery in another company.

00:43:57.535 --> 00:44:01.370
I mean how come that this is
still such a big issue in the

00:44:01.370 --> 00:44:03.660
e-commerce world?

00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:06.480
HIROSHI MIKITANI: Well, so even
if you say free shipping,

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.000
the question is is it really
shipping or not, right?

00:44:14.430 --> 00:44:19.350
Unless you find some arbitrage
opportunity by bundling or

00:44:19.350 --> 00:44:24.330
some creative way to make
your cost structure more

00:44:24.330 --> 00:44:25.840
competitive than
against other--

00:44:25.840 --> 00:44:30.910
it's really automation, for
example, or something--

00:44:30.910 --> 00:44:34.700
then you can absorb the
cost into your gross

00:44:34.700 --> 00:44:36.980
margin of your product.

00:44:36.980 --> 00:44:44.300
And that has not been
proven yet I think.

00:44:44.300 --> 00:44:49.150
So if you just keep buying
toothbrush, one toothbrush

00:44:49.150 --> 00:44:54.780
every single day, you're going
to be extremely unprofitable.

00:44:54.780 --> 00:44:59.720
So I think we need to
find a way to make

00:44:59.720 --> 00:45:02.720
economically work for that.

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:05.760
And I think that's very,
very challenging.

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:07.690
Because it's not free
as a matter of fact

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:09.570
for the service provider.

00:45:09.570 --> 00:45:11.400
That means it's not
fundamentally

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:13.050
free for the end customer.

00:45:13.050 --> 00:45:19.180
You are either paying the
membership fee, annual

00:45:19.180 --> 00:45:22.160
membership fee, like
Amazon Prime.

00:45:22.160 --> 00:45:29.160
Or your are basically paying a
higher price fundamentally

00:45:29.160 --> 00:45:35.630
speaking or maybe you are
getting other sort of a profit

00:45:35.630 --> 00:45:39.490
source for the service
provider.

00:45:39.490 --> 00:45:43.560
And that's all about
I think arbitrage.

